04594nam a22006375i 9780674270039DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222022mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742700397 a10.4159/97806742700392doi  a(DE-B1597)609918  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHC125b.F337 2022eb 7aHIS0240002bisacsh04a338.982231 aFajardo, Margarita, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe World That Latin America Created :bThe United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America in the Development Era /cMargarita Fajardo. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHarvard Historical Studies ;v19200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Latin America and the Postwar Global Order -- t2. Center and Periphery in Action -- t3. “Structuralism,” “Monetarism,” and the Politics of Inflation -- t4. Revolutions Left and Right -- t5. Toward Dependency Theory -- t6. The Many Lives of Dependency Theory -- tEpilogue: Dependency Theory in the World and Back in Latin America -- tArchives -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow a group of intellectuals and policymakers transformed development economics and gave Latin America a new position in the world. After the Second World War demolished the old order, a group of economists and policymakers from across Latin America imagined a new global economy and launched an intellectual movement that would eventually capture the world. They charged that the systems of trade and finance that bound the world’s nations together were frustrating the economic prospects of Latin America and other regions of the world. Through the UN Economic Commission for Latin America, or CEPAL, the Spanish and Portuguese acronym, cepalinos challenged the orthodoxies of development theory and policy. Simultaneously, they demanded more not less trade, more not less aid, and offered a development agenda to transform both the developed and the developing world. Eventually, cepalinos established their own form of hegemony, outpacing the United States and the International Monetary Fund as the agenda setters for a region traditionally held under the orbit of Washington and its institutions. By doing so, cepalinos reshaped both regional and international governance and set an intellectual agenda that still resonates today. Drawing on unexplored sources from the Americas and Europe, Margarita Fajardo retells the history of dependency theory, revealing the diversity of an often-oversimplified movement and the fraught relationship between cepalinos, their dependentista critics, and the regional and global Left. By examining the political ventures of dependentistas and cepalinos, The World That Latin America Created is a story of ideas that brought about real change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDependency. 0aEconomic developmentzLatin AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311078579140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674270039zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674270039423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674270039/original  a978-3-11-078579-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK